Poverty and Death in Indonesia's Golden Land
Bardina Degei doesn't use a stove when she cooks.
He rarely even uses a bowl.
The housewife puts a sweet potato, commonly known locally as a "note", directly on the fire in her wooden house in Enarotali, Paniai regency, in the restless region of Papua, Indonesia.
After half an hour, the roasted lump is removed and wiped with appetite, hands are not washed.
Degei sits on the muddy floor where he does chores like laundry with fuzzy water from the nearby swamp, with no furniture.
It's like a bucket of desert toilets in a house without a roof.
As the youngest of the four wives of her husband, she was not assigned to any field.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: most of the men in the village are unemployed, many are drinking too much, and there are soldiers.
"Nobody walks around the village after 5:00 p.m.," he says.
A rare snapshot of everyday life in the mountainous areas of Papua, a former Dutch colony absorbed by Indonesia in 1969 following a controversial referendum in which only 1026 seniors were forced to vote by force before the troops invaded.
A current movement that is propagandizing independence against the Dutch administration has quickly turned its anger against the Jakarta government, which maintains strict control over the region and bans foreign journalists or rights watchdogs.
In 2003, the region was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, as independent Papua New Guinea would occupy the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is as isolated as it is remote; the journey here includes a 90-minute flight from the regional capital Jayapura to Nabire and a 5-hour stomach-wrenching car ride with a rental car.
No public transport.
The 19,000-seat resort contains wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, with wrinkled iron roofs turned into various shades of yellowish brown by rust.
Let's leave the journalists, very few Indonesians have traveled here, and almost no foreigner has ever traveled here.
Before the Christian missionaries arrived, Mee Pago worshipped a god named Uga Tamee.
There have been other changes.
"We were not used to wearing these clothes," Degei said, referring to his vibrant, hand-woven turban, dark shirt and shiny skirt.
"We used to wear only leaves on our bodies."
Papua is the poorest region in Indonesia, where 28% of people live below the poverty line, with the worst child deaths and literacy rates in Asia.
But at the same time, this is Indonesia's golden land.
The largest and most profitable gold mine in the world, owned by Phoenix-based Freeport McMoran, Grasberg is located just 60 miles from Paniai, a mountainous region the size of New Jersey and home to 153,000 people.
In 2015 alone, Freeport produced about $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
In addition, Papua has an estimated $78 billion in lumber reserves.
However, these riches, which are a source of misery for the Papuans, allow the powerful army of Indonesia to maintain a suffocating presence.
The New York Times’ 2005 research reports that Freeport paid about $20 million to local military personnel and units between 1998 and 2004, including up to $150,000 paid to a single officer.
The more autonomy of the Papuans threatens this golden egg-laying hen and is being mercilessly deprived of its rights.
Since 1969, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed by the Indonesian military and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned.
Mass killings in the 1970s in the mountainous parts of Papua reached the figures of genocide, according to the Asian Human Rights Commission.
Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful demonstrators in the region last year alone.
The Brisbane Archdiocese’s “We’ll Lose Everything” report in 2016 contains testimony of misdemeanors such as unlawful executions, torture (especially popular with rape and electricity, according to another report), and brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
"It's hard to count the number of victims because there are incidents every week," says Andreas Harsono, an Indonesian researcher at Human Rights Watch.
The pressure increased as Papua's resources brought settlers from other parts of Indonesia.
83% of the region's 3.5 million population is Christian, but the demographics change as Muslim migrants from Indonesia's densely populated islands Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi come for economic purposes.
Java warung buffets sell gado-gado served with peanut sauce mixed with fried chicken and vegetables.
The locals are struggling to compete.
"Immigrants sell chicken and vegetables in traditional markets cheaper than native Papuans," explains Abeth You, a 24-year-old native of Paniai, who moved for business to the regional capital Jayapura.
"This caused the native Papuans to lose their Papuan mama-mama (females) to the market."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, more commonly known as Jokowi, promised to resolve the inequalities and rights violations in Papua during his 2014 election campaign.
As the former carpenter headed for the presidential palace in Jakarta, 27 of Papua’s 29 districts, including Panaia, received votes.
But very little has changed in Papua, and today the locals feel cheated.
“Our hearts are broken because we voted for Jokowi in 2014 in hopes that he would realize our hope of justice being restored,” You said.
In fact, Paniai experienced his worst state only two months after Jokowi took office in October.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children outside singing Christmas songs in front of a fire in Enarotali broke through two Indonesian military darkness on a motorcycle.
The frightened kids told them to turn on their headlights.
One of the soldiers resented his style, and according to local priest Yavedt Thebai, he later returned with four soldiers.
Victims and eyewitnesses said the soldiers who had been drinking chased the group and beat them with their rifles.
Then one of the soldiers shot at the group of children.
One of the children, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, the nearby government election commission building was set on fire, and the following day the events escalated.
About 1,000 Papuan men, women and children gathered to demand justice on a football field in front of the local police station and military command center.
They carried ceremonial hunting bows and performed the waita dance of the Mee Pago tribe of Papua (running in the form of a ring and imitating the singing of birds).
Some protesters began throwing stones at the police and the military garrison.
As the nerves grew more tense, an order was sent to the soldiers via internal radio: "If the crowd resists more than three times, shoot and kill them." An official document seen by TIME, which was not disclosed to the local media, said.
Jeremias Kayame (56), head of the Kego Koto neighborhood in Enarotali, saw the imminent danger and prayed to the crowd to return home, demanding calm.
No one was willing to listen.
On the porch of his brightly painted wooden house, he told TIME, "When I turned around, I was suddenly shot in the left wrist."
Kayame still doesn’t know who fired, but says the bullet came from the collected military era.
"It was crowded, shot many times," he added.
According to his cousin, who witnessed the attacks, native Alfius Youw was shot three times.
"I ran to him and examined his body to make sure it was him," Yohanes, known by only one name, told TIME pessimistly.
"I saw you die... I kissed her."
Papua Police Chief Inspector General Yotje Mende told reporters that his officers only "secured" the police station because the police station was under attack.
"When people threaten to kill us, we have to defend ourselves," said Papua police spokesman Pudjo Sulistio in 2015.
"It's a matter of life and death."
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many were injured.
The news of the deaths reached Jakarta only the next day.
Jokowi gave an enthusiastic speech three weeks later in Jayapura, expressing sympathy for the victims' families and promising to resolve the historical abuses in Papua.
"I want this case resolved immediately so it won't happen again in the future."
Security Minister Wiranto said in October 2016 that he had set up a non-forensic mechanism for historical human rights violations.
The excuses began almost immediately.
"Most of the violations happened a long time ago.
Some in the 90s and some in the early 2000s.
The point is that we are determined to resolve these violations, but there are processes that we have to go through.”
Speaking to TIME on June 5, Wiranto stepped back, saying he had no plans to set up a complaint mechanism in Papua.
Instead, he said, "It'll all be settled by the law."
Wiranto, whom the UN accused of "crimes against humanity" related to more than 1,000 deaths during East Timor's bloody 1999 independence vote, said 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua, including the Paniai incident, have already been resolved.
The families of the Paniai victims responded with bitter skepticism to such claims.
"I've been interviewed four times in the past three years, but no progress has been made," says Yohanes.
"I'm tired."
Years later, he says, he's still living in fear.
He says, "I'm scared."
"I'm afraid of being arrested by the military, I'm afraid of being shot."
His brother Yacobus repeats his view that people in Paniai are afraid to discuss the incident.
He says he was beaten by a soldier after helping to bury four of the victims.
"After burying the corpses, the soldier came looking for me," he says.
The attacks haven't stopped yet.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police fired on villagers at Paniai's neighbor, the Deiyai regency.
During a clash between the villagers and the director of a construction company who refused to help a man who was not himself, one person was killed and 17 others were injured, including children.
24-year-old Ravianus Douw, who drowned in a nearby lake while fishing, died on his way to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested outside the company's construction site office.
The police said the villagers threw stones at the officers and they reacted with a warning shot.
But locals say the moving brigade (Indonesian paramilitary police) opened fire on the crowd and killed someone.
Dominggu Badii, 29, who lives close to the hospital and witnessed the upbringing of the wounded, told TIME: "We were very panicked, we were afraid of revenge."
"I've been hiding in my house for two days."
The Deiyai parliament has called for the officials involved to be held accountable and the moving police brigade to be withdrawn from the area.
Paniai has always been a problem area for the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development nurtures the discontent of the Mee, Moni, Dani, and Damal tribal peoples who live scattered along Papua's green mountainous center.
Many joined the rebel army Free Papua Movement (OPM), which claimed to protect the rights of the Papuans by random attacks and kidnapping raids on Indonesian soldiers.
Some of the top OPM leaders, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya, come from Paniai.
In response, thousands of people in Paniai were arrested and arbitrarily held by soldiers in recent years under the guise of "protecting national sovereignty".
Some are never seen again.
Among the peoples of Papua, Paniai is known as a "tragic and forgotten place".
Poverty feeds dissatisfaction.
A little rice on sale at Enarotali is too expensive for the locals to buy.
Bread is inaccessible.
People here grow everything they eat: mainly the note, as well as some fruit and leafy vegetables.
Farming is the work of women who can sustain four or five fields of sweet potatoes.
They usually keep most of the harvest for the family, selling the rest in the local market.
Ten notes make only 10,000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Over time, economic inequalities between native Papuans and new immigrants have increased since the opening of new air routes to Nabire Airport.
Jobs that are already scarce often go to immigrants who are better educated and richer.
Papuans rarely have the capital or the necessary qualifications to run their own business competitively.
"Young people are not interested in staying in the village because there is no work or money here," said John Gobai, president of the Panai tribal council.
Isolation keeps the eyes of the world away from Papua.
In addition, the reporting restrictions for international media remain tightly in place.
Earlier this year, French journalist Franck Escudie and Basille Longchamp were deported from Papua due to "lack of coordination with relevant institutions" despite their rarely-given permission to shoot videos.
According to Phelim Kine, Assistant Director of Human Rights Watch Asia, Jokowi’s campaign promises of lifting the restrictions on newsmaking and development have not been fulfilled in order to increase its transparency.
"There are new dangers for foreign journalists who are trying to make news from the restless eastern end provinces of Indonesia, Papua and West Papua: visa denial and blacklisting," he said in a statement.
The lack of press supervision means that the international pressure on the Indonesian government is mostly limited to its neighbors near Papua.
In March, six Pacific nations (Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, Marshall Islands, and Solomon Islands) urged the UN Human Rights Council to investigate "various and widespread violations" in Papua, including Panaia attacks.
The same countries have historically supported OPM.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Arrmanata Nasir told reporters in Jakarta that "the democratic system in Indonesia is still in place and there are free media, so it is difficult to cover up the evidence in human rights cases."
Locals want more foreign governments to take care of them.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands visited Jayapura on May 4, headed by the country's human rights envoy, Kees Van Baar, the locals broke their silence in their plea "We want freedom," according to a source who attended the meeting and did not want to be named.
Indonesia has another presidential election in 2019, but the Papuans say they are unlikely to vote for Jokowi again.
"Jokowi is a person with good intentions, but he is surrounded by people involved in the Paniai attack," says tribal council president Gobai.
He wants Jokowi to know that, apart from living under the imminent threat of a tyrannical soldier, the Paniai people are rolling around with little education and health care and fakru necessity.
Gobai says the Paniai people, like other Papuans, see their vote as a “debt” to Jokowi to pay back.
“They don’t need money, they just want justice.”
Despite the threats and intimidation, the families of the victims of the Paniai attack carried out one last symbolic act of resistance: burying a victim’s body in the land opposite the police and military outpost.
Knowing that justice may never be done, they will at least make sure that those responsible do not forget their crimes.
"A member of our family was killed," Yacobus says, head down.
"What else can we do?"
