New Results of Sweden’s Asylum Age Assessment Test
The latest results of assessment tests of refugees subjected to a new medical age assessment method in Sweden found that more than 80 percent of those who took the test were over the age of 18, but not everyone is confident in the accuracy of these tests.
Sweden’s national Forensic Medicine and Drug Administration (Rättsmedicalverket) began testing earlier this year.
The tests were designed to make the age assessment in the asylum process more accurate after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) criticized the failures of some refugees to assess their right age.
To date, Migrationsverket has sent 6880 cases to the test, and the Forensic Medicine and Drug Administration has now announced the results of a total of 2481 from the period from mid-March to July 31, 2017.
It was found that 80 percent of them were 18 or above, and in 25 cases, the Forensic Medicine and Drug Administration ruled that the subject was "probably 18 or above".
In 432 cases, the result was that the person was “probably under 18.”
The tests were conducted only in cases where the person’s age was suspect.
According to Johan Göransson of the Forensic Medicine and Drug Administration, the results are consistent with past months.
"We don't see a big difference in statistics over the past months, the numbers are pretty consistent," he told The Local.
The high rate of cases that are judged to be over 18 does not necessarily mean that refugees are lying about their age.
In May, the department announced the results of the 581 tests and said there were 442 cases "in which the study showed that people were 18 years of age or older".
When the Svenska Dagbladet newspaper examined the results of the 581 reported cases, it found that 243 reportedly turned 18 this year.
The method of medical age assessment, which involves x-raying the 20-year-old teeth and performing an MRI of the knee joints, and then having dentists and radiologists analyze them, is criticized in some circles.
One of the skeptics is the endocrinologist of the Karolinska Institute, Claude Marcus, who evaluated the biological maturity of people with studies on whether or not they entered the age of puberty earlier or later than usual.
“I have reasons to think about it, and I don’t think the type of measurement used should be that.
It's very dubious to decide biological age this way.
If we can’t say it for sure, we shouldn’t pretend it is,” he told the Metro newspaper.
However, Göransson, from the Forensic Medicine and Drug Administration, defended the accuracy of the tests: “In general, you might say that the risk of a child being misjudged as an adult is small.
The greatest risk is that the person is just under the age of 18, in which case the risk is around 10 percent.”
