He used camouflage to avoid dinosaur enemies.
At first glance, it looks like a statue, but it's a terrible one.
The researchers explained that the initial findings of an incredible rhinoceros-sized creature now found by a Canadian miner were very well preserved, as experts described it as the “Mona Lisa of the dinosaurs.”
They were so well-preserved that they could tell that the scale skin was reddish brown and that they had a 'problematic history'.
A report in the journal Current Biology described it as “the best preserved armored dinosaur found and one of the best dinosaur breeds in the world.”
The fossil is a newly discovered species of nodozor that lived around 110 million to 112 million years ago from the middle of the Cretaceous Period.
His exceptionally well-preserved condition has astounded researchers who have described him as “really wonderful.”
The plant-eating armor is the best-preserved fossil of its kind, according to reports from National Geographic.
He was found by Shawn Funk on March 21, 2011 in North Alberta Canada, digging the Suncor Millenium Mine near Fort McMurray.
He hit something that seemed strange to the rock around him and decided to take a closer look.
The fossil was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum.
They spent the next six years discovering a wild animal in a heap of 2,500 pounds (1100 kg) of soil.
After so much hard work, the finished result is now ready to be revealed.
Caleb Brown, the lead scientist at the Royal Tyrrell Museum, where the creature was exhibited, said, “If you close your eyes a little, you might even believe it’s almost asleep.”
'It will go down in the history of science as one of the most beautiful and best preserved dinosaur species, the Mona Lisa of the dinosaurs.'
By examining its skin, the researchers found that although it was coated with armor and looked like a walking tank, the plant eater was probably facing a serious threat from meat-eating dinosaurs.
Quite heavily armored, the dinosaur used its red and white camouflage to hide from predators, and a protective technique known as contra-shadowing, which many modern-day animals also use.
Experts suggest that it was hunted by larger dinosaurs, allowing it to better blend into its surroundings and bypass its enemies.
The 110-million-year-old nodozor family first made headlines in May and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum.
The researchers have now finished their work, and they named the wild animal Borealopelta markmitchelli, dedicated to museum technician Mark Mitchell, one of the team who spent more than 7,000 hours laboriously trying to uncover it.
The exceptional preservation of the species made it possible for Dr. Mitchell and his international team of scientists to document the pattern and shape of the stamps and the armor on the body.
They discovered counter-shadowing, a common defense method in the animal kingdom, meaning that the upper part of the creature is darker than the lower part.
Although counter-shadowing is common, the findings come as a surprise because the size of Borealopelta far exceeds that of counter-shadowed animals that are alive today.
This means that the dinosaur has been under enough pressure from meat-eating dinosaurs to hunt, and that evolution has preferred to hide as a method of survival to confront.
But the most contemporary animals (e.g. deer, zebras, or armadillos) that use counter-shadowing are much smaller and are much more open to being prey, which means that this nodozor has faced a serious challenge to survive.
"The powerful hunting applied to a huge, heavy-armoured animal shows how dangerous dinosaur predators in the Cretaceous can be," Brown said.
Chemical analysis of the organic compounds in the scales also revealed that the dinosaur's skin was reddish brown.
Scientists continue to study the animal for clues about its life, including its preserved intestinal contents, to find out what it ate at its last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, it fell into a river and drifted into the sea, where it sank on its back to the surface of the ocean.
At that time, Alberta was as hot as South Florida is today, and rivers and oceans were probably far more inland than they are now.
"The nodozor is truly remarkable because it is completely covered and preserved with scaly skin, but also because the original shape of the animal is preserved in a 3D way," Brown said.
The result is that the animal looks almost the same today as it did in the early Cretaceous.
You don’t need much imagination to rebuild it; if you close your eyes a little, you might even believe it’s almost asleep.”
The Cretaceous was the time when giant theropods, meat-eating dinosaurs standing on two legs, roamed the Earth.
Although king of them all, Tyrannosaurus rex lived millions of years after the armored dinosaur Borealopelta, which may have been hunted by some of its majestic ancestors.
Among them is the Acrocanthosaurus, a 38 ft (11.5m) long, 6 tons-weighted monster.
Scientists, whose latest findings are in the journal Current Biology, believe that Borealopelta was dragged into the sea after she died and mummified in mud.
