Researchers believe that this armored herbaceous vortex was a cumbersome roaming around what is now Western Canada until it was dragged into the open sea by a overflowing river.
But the dinosaur's underwater tomb preserved its armor in perfect detail.
The fossilized remains of this particular species are so well preserved that the skin fragments still cover layers of bumpy armor along the dinosaur’s skull.
As Michael Greshko wrote for National Geographic, such a degree of preservation is as rare as winning the lottery.
