While patients are often advised to skip meat and dairy products to alleviate their symptoms, researchers at the University of Washington found that the protein’s main amino acid, tryptophan, helps develop immune cells that develop a durable gut.
Lead researcher Dr. Marco Colonna said that immune cells patrol the intestines to prevent microbes hidden in food from sneaking into the body.
Cells that are capable of triggering inflammation are balanced with cells that promote stamina by protecting sensitive tissues without damaging them.
If the balance shifts too much to the inflammation, it can result from inflammatory bowel disease.
In the experiments, it was found that some kind of immune cell that promotes endurance in mice carrying a specific bacteria in their intestines.
And the bacteria needs tryptophan, one of the building blocks of the protein, to trigger the emergence of cells.
Professor Colonna said: “We have established a link between the bacterial species Lactobacillus reuteri, which is part of the gut microbiome, and the development of the cell population that promotes endurance.”
The mice who had more tryptophan in their diet had more of these immune cells.”
If the same is happening in humans, L. reuteri and tryptophan-rich diets could improve a more durable, less inflammatory bowel environment.
Postdoctoral researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas studied a type of immune cell that improves endurance, and discovered that a group of experimental mice had these types of cells, but no other group of the same species, which were kept in a different place, had them.
He suspected that the difference was related to the mice’s gut microbiomes, in other words, the bacteria, viruses, and fungi communities that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract.
DNA sequences of the mice's intestines were performed and found that in mice with immune cells, there were six species of bacteria, but they were not.
Rats who lack an intestinal microbiome because they are cared for in a sterile environment and do not develop such an immune cell were given L. reuteri and immune cells emerged.
To understand how the bacteria affects the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in liquid and then transferred it to immature immune cells from mice in small amounts from this non-bacterial liquid.
Immune cells have evolved into cells that promote endurance.
The active ingredient turned out to be a by-product of tryptophan metabolism known as indole-3-lactic acid when it was purified from liquid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice’s food, the number of cells increased by about 50 percent, but when tryptophan levels were reduced by half, the number of cells fell by half.
Dr Cervantes-Barragan said that humans have cells that promote the same endurance as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in the gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known if tryptophan by-products from L. reuteri have developed in humans as well as in mice, but disorders in the genes associated with tryptophan have been found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
